Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Peel and thinly slice the @sweet potatoes{1}(peeled and thinly sliced) into ¼-inch rounds. On a #baking sheet{}, toss the sweet potatoes with @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Roast for ~{20-25%minutes}, until golden brown and tender, flipping half way through.

Meanwhile, peel the @cucumber{1}(peeled) and halve lengthwise, then scoop the seeds out with a #spoon{}. Dice the cucumber and @honeydew melon{4%ounce} into ¼-inch cubes. Mince the @shallot{1}(minced) and @mint{1%sprig}(minced). Zest and halve the @lime{1}(zested and halved).

== Honeydew-Cucumber Salsa ==

Make the honeydew-cucumber salsa: in a #medium bowl{}, toss the honeydew, mint, half the cucumber, half the shallot (or less, to taste), and the juice of half the lime. Season with salt and pepper.

== Citronette ==

Make the citronette: in a #small bowl{}, whisk together @olive oil{2%tbsp}, the lime zest, the juice of the remaining lime, the remaining shallot, and a pinch of salt and pepper.

== Salmon ==

Heat @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Season the @salmon fillets{2%skin-on} with salt and pepper on both sides, then add to the pan and cook ~{3-4%minutes} per side, until golden brown and just opaque in the center.

== Assembly ==

Toss the @watercress{4%ounce}, remaining cucumber, and roasted sweet potatoes with the citronette, then top with the salmon and honeydew-cucumber salsa. Enjoy!

> Forget what you know about salsa—this version turns your traditional tomato salsa upside-down with refreshing crunch, minty brightness, and subtle sweetness. Served atop flaky salmon and crispy roasted sweet potatoes, you'll be pleasantly surprised with this unusual combination of flavors.